% ===== Page 2 =====
\subsubsection*{13.1.2 Generation, projectivity, exchangeability}

\textbf{Option 1}

The most straightforward generation option simply follows Definition 13.2:

\begin{center}
\textit{[Figure: A diagram showing a one-dimensional line segment from $O$ to $r$ with points labeled $\mathcal{X}_5$, $\mathcal{X}_8$, $\mathcal{X}_9$, $\mathcal{X}_7$, $\mathcal{X}_{13}$ placed along it. Above the points are curved arcs connecting consecutive points, suggesting connections or intervals between them. The diagram is overlaid on a grid background.]}
\end{center}

This option is fine in practice, but not in theory because:

\begin{enumerate}
\item[(a)] It is finitely exchangeable, so there is no limit (thanks to the Aldous-Hoover theorem) since graphs are sparse (in practical terms, $U[0,n](x) = 1/n \to 0$ at $n \to \infty$).

\item[(b)] The point process is binomial, so there are dependencies between the numbers of points in non-overlapping intervals.
\end{enumerate}

The point process in this option is called \textit{binomial} because the number of points in an interval of length $l < n$ is $\text{Bin}[n, p]$ with $p = l/n$.

Solution to problem (b): Adjust the process to be a \textit{Poisson point process (PPP)}.

\textbf{Definition 13.3.} A point process is \textit{Poisson} of rate 1 if:

\begin{enumerate}
\item[1.] the number of points in any interval of length $l$ is Poisson$[l]$,

\item[2.] the numbers of points in any two non-overlapping intervals are independent.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Option 2}

\begin{enumerate}
\item[1.] Sample $n \sim \text{Poisson}[\bar{n}]$, where $\bar{n} > 0$,

\item[2.] proceed to option 1.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Theorem 13.4.} \textit{Option 2 implements the Poisson point process of rate 1 on $[0,\bar{n}]$.}

This option solves the second problem with option 1, but it is still not ideal, because:

\begin{enumerate}
\item[(a)] it does not solve problem (a) of option 1, and

\item[(b)] the graph size $n$ is now random.
\end{enumerate}

Solution to both problem (a\&b) of option 2:
Implement the PPP in the projective (growing) manner, option 3.

\textbf{Option 3}

\begin{enumerate}
\item[1.] Set $x_0 = 0$

\item[2.] For $n = 1, 2, ...$,
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(a)] sample $d \sim \exp[1](d) = e^{-d}$, $d \geq 0$,
\item[(b)] set $x_n = x_{n-1} + d$
\item[(c)] for $(i = n-1, |x_n - x_i| < r, i--)$
\begin{enumerate}
\item[i.] connect $n$ to $i$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Theorem 13.5.} \textit{Option 3 implements the PPP of rate 1 on $\mathbb{R}^+$ with points labeled in the increasing order of their coordinates:}

\begin{center}
\textit{[Figure: A diagram showing a one-dimensional line starting from $O$ with points labeled $\mathcal{X}_1$, $\mathcal{X}_2$, and $\mathcal{X}_4$ placed along it. Above the points are curved arcs connecting points within a certain range, suggesting connections based on proximity. Below the line, $\mathcal{X}_6$ is shown. The diagram is overlaid on a grid background.]}
\end{center}

\vspace{1em}

\begin{center}
67
\end{center}

\newpage

% ===== Page 3 =====
\textbf{Notes:}

\begin{itemize}
  \item $x_n \neq n$, but $\langle x_n \rangle = n$.
    \begin{itemize}
      \item $x_n \sim \text{Gamma}[\text{mean} = n, \text{rate} = 1](x) = \frac{x^{n-1}}{(n-1)!} e^{-x}$ -- the distribution of the sum of $n$ exponentials.
      \item We can't fix both $n$ and $[0, n]$: either/or, please!
    \end{itemize}
  
  \item Option 3 is an algorithm that, if run to infinity generates an infinite RGG.
  
  \item \textit{An algorithmic perspective on projectivity}: a network model is \textit{projective} if there exists an algorithm that
    \begin{itemize}
      \item is growing, i.e., builds the graph by adding nodes iteratively, e.g., one at a time;
      \item does not alter (non)links among already existing nodes;
      \item if let run to infinity, generates an infinite graph in the model.
    \end{itemize}
  
  \item If the model is not projective, such an algorithm does NOT exist; examples:
    \begin{itemize}
      \item $\mathcal{G}(n, p)$ with $p = k/n$, where $k = \text{const}$;
      \item HSCM with $\gamma \neq 3$;
      \item RGGs in the exchangeable formulation in options 1 or 2.
    \end{itemize}
  
  \item In the projective option 3 formulation, the RGGs are NOT exchangeable, which is OK because node labels DO matter.
  
  \item For any finite $n$, we can easily go from projective to exchangeable formulations and back:
    \begin{enumerate}
      \item Projective $\to$ exchangeable: permute node labels randomly: select uniformly at random, with probability $1/n!$, one label permutation out of $n!$ possibilities.
      \item Exchangeable $\to$ projective: sort the node labels in the increasing order of their coordinates.
    \end{enumerate}
  
  \item If $n = \infty$, then (2) the exchangeable formulation does not exist, and (1) does not work either because the number of permutations $\infty! = \infty$, and so $1/\infty! = 0$: it is impossible to select a random permutation.
  
  \item These points are very general and apply to any projective model that expands in space (e.g., SPA=HSCM with $\gamma = 3$); the difference is only in $p(x, x')$.
  
  \item The sparse projective RGGs and their derivatives below can be defined in any space of infinite volume (e.g., $\mathbb{R}^d$, $\mathbb{H}^d$, non-compact Riemannian or Lorentzian manifolds), so we can shove an infinite number of nodes at constant density into them.
  
  \item In what follows, the space is one-dimensional ($\mathbb{R}^+$) for simplicity.
\end{itemize}

